1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:15,851
Two American astronauts awaiting their return flight from the International Space Station (ISS) have stayed busy carrying out a series of scientific experiments.

2
00:00:15,851 --> 00:00:30,960
The U.S. space agency NASA has said the pair – Butch Wilmore and Suni Williams – will remain at the ISS until late March or early April.

3
00:00:30,960 --> 00:00:43,680
When they arrived at the orbiting laboratory in June 2024, the astronauts expected to stay in space for just one week.

4
00:00:43,680 --> 00:00:50,970
Their trip was a test flight of Boeing’s Starliner spacecraft.

5
00:00:50,970 --> 00:01:09,448
While Starliner safely transported the two to the ISS, the spacecraft had several problems that persuaded NASA to send it back to Earth for further testing without the astronauts onboard.

6
00:01:09,448 --> 00:01:21,924
NASA’s current plan calls for Wilmore and Williams to fly back on a SpaceX spacecraft in late March at the earliest.

7
00:01:21,924 --> 00:01:34,718
NASA has been using SpaceX’s Crew Dragon to regularly carry astronauts and supplies to the ISS since 2020.

8
00:01:34,718 --> 00:01:42,171
The astronauts have been using their extended mission to carry out experiments.

9
00:01:42,171 --> 00:01:51,044
In addition, Williams stepped out of the space station earlier this month to complete a spacewalk.

10
00:01:51,044 --> 00:02:03,597
Another NASA astronaut, Nick Hague, joined Williams on the spacewalk on January 16, the agency said in a statement.

11
00:02:03,597 --> 00:02:11,453
The two repaired a piece of equipment that helps guide the movements of the ISS.

12
00:02:11,453 --> 00:02:23,564
The spacewalk also included work on an X-ray telescope, as well as maintenance activities for other ISS systems.

13
00:02:23,564 --> 00:02:31,840
NASA noted it was the fourth spacewalk for Hague and the eighth for Williams.

14
00:02:31,840 --> 00:02:41,511
The space agency said Williams was preparing for another spacewalk planned for January 30.

15
00:02:41,511 --> 00:02:52,792
Wilmore is expected to join Williams on that spacewalk, which NASA estimates will last about six-and-a-half hours.

16
00:02:52,792 --> 00:02:58,858
The two will be aiming to remove a radio antenna structure.

17
00:02:58,858 --> 00:03:07,457
They will also be “searching for microbes” around the ISS for use in experiments.

18
00:03:07,457 --> 00:03:15,620
Here is a look at other experiments Wilmore and Williams have completed during their stay.

19
00:03:15,620 --> 00:03:23,861
NASA said Wilmore and Williams have tested different methods for growing crops in space.

20
00:03:23,861 --> 00:03:31,917
Such methods could support humans who have longer stays in space in the future.

21
00:03:31,917 --> 00:03:38,115
One experiment is called the Plant Water Management investigation.

22
00:03:38,115 --> 00:03:51,759
NASA said this experiment “uses the physical properties of fluids…to overcome the lack of gravity and provide hydration to plants.”

23
00:03:51,759 --> 00:04:01,970
The experiment aims to help NASA develop hydroponic systems to support future space missions.

24
00:04:01,970 --> 00:04:14,721
Another experiment examines a new way to grow vegetables, plants and flowers inside the ISS to provide nutrition and beauty.

25
00:04:14,721 --> 00:04:23,414
As part of this experiment, Wilmore installed a new light meter inside the ISS.

26
00:04:23,414 --> 00:04:34,133
The device is designed to measure available light and to help crew members improve growing operations.

27
00:04:34,133 --> 00:04:46,567
NASA also said that throughout the current mission, Williams had deployed and observed three free-flying robots called Astrobee.

28
00:04:46,567 --> 00:04:59,276
This robotic experiment seeks to examine how such robots could assist astronauts with daily duties and maintenance work.

29
00:04:59,276 --> 00:05:17,241
The agency said the square-shaped robots are designed to help scientists and engineers develop and test new robotic technologies for use in microgravity environments.

30
00:05:17,241 --> 00:05:31,463
The assistants are also designed to help astronauts with daily tasks “and give ground controllers additional eyes and ears on the space station.”

31
00:05:31,463 --> 00:05:41,646
Williams tested the robots’ ability to map the inside of the space station and Astrobee’s flight abilities.

32
00:05:41,646 --> 00:05:52,337
NASA astronauts visiting the ISS have a long history of capturing images of Earth from space.

33
00:05:52,337 --> 00:05:58,002
And this is another activity Wilmore and Williams have carried out.

34
00:05:58,002 --> 00:06:09,501
The ISS gives astronauts a “window to the world” as they orbit 400 kilometers above their home planet.

35
00:06:09,501 --> 00:06:27,416
During their mission, NASA said the two astronauts had “captured hundreds of photographs of Earth, ranging from auroras, land, sea, orbital sunrises and sunsets, and more.”

36
00:06:27,416 --> 00:06:40,817
Another space station tradition is for U.S. astronauts to connect with students and other interested individuals during their stay in space.

37
00:06:40,817 --> 00:06:56,853
They have virtual visits with people back on Earth who can ask the astronauts how it feels to live in space and can learn about NASA’s experiments aboard the ISS.

38
00:06:56,853 --> 00:07:07,673
In early August, Williams used ham radio technology to connect with students from Banda Aceh, Indonesia.

39
00:07:07,673 --> 00:07:18,960
NASA explained that students get the chance to communicate with the astronauts when the ISS passes overhead.

40
00:07:18,960 --> 00:07:30,880
The students can ask about research on the ISS as well as the radio wave technology that makes the communication possible.

41
00:07:30,880 --> 00:07:33,851
I’m Bryan Lynn.